fr.reflexe.viewshell.api.http

Interface IHttpService

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IHttpEndPoint

    @SystemService
public interface IHttpService
extends IHttpEndPoint
    Provides high-level access to the embedded HTTP server.

    Incoming requests are delegated to implementations of IAddressableService. Such implementations must be made available to the HTTP service via the OSGi Service Registry.

    Thread safety: implementations are required to be safe for concurrent read/write access.

    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    REFLEXE Technologies

    • Method Detail

      • isUsingSessionCookies

        boolean isUsingSessionCookies()
        Indicates whether sessions should try to use cookies.

        By default, for compliance with the European "e-Privacy" Directive 2009/136/EC, this feature is NOT enabled

        When session cookies are not used, URL rewriting should be used instead, either by using IHttpServiceCall.encodeUrl(CharSequence) or a template function.

        This does not prevent any other use of cookies.

        Returns:
        true if the server should try to use cookies for session identifiers, otherwise false (the default setting).
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        IConfigService.isServerUsingSessionCookies(), IHttpServiceCall.encodeUrl(CharSequence)

      • verifyHostName

        String verifyHostName(String hostName)
               throws IllegalArgumentException
        Verifies a host name string to check that it has a valid format, and transforms IDNs (International Domain Names) to ACE (ASCII-Compatible Encoding, also referred to as "punycode") when necessary.

        General DNS rules are:

        • No domain name can have an overall length greater than 253 characters.
        • No label (dot-separated part of the overall domain name) may be longer than 63 characters.

        An attempt will be made to convert names containing non-LDH ("letters, digits, hyphens") characters into ACE ("punycode") form within the allowed ranges, when the hostname contains such characters.

        Parameters:
        hostName - host name to verify.
        Returns:
        the supplied hostname if containing only LDH characters, or the ACE form if using characters from international character sets. Therefore, to determine if a hostname requires ACE (punycode), compare the input to this method with this method's output.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the hostname does not comply with general DNS rules, or if it cannot be converted to ACE (for example, if the supplied hostname contains unassigned Unicode code points).

      • getFileContentType

        IContentType getFileContentType(CharSequence fileName)
        Where possible, gets a value for a HTTP Content-Type header based on a given filename (based on known filename extension mappings), including (where relevant) character set information.

        Character set information can only be included for text/* or application/* MIME types. The default character set of UTF-8 is normally applied for text types.

        Parameters:
        fileName - the non-null filename.
        Returns:
        the best-match MIME type based on known filename extension mappings.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        getFileMediaType(CharSequence), getFileContentType(CharSequence, String)

      • getFileContentType

        IContentType getFileContentType(CharSequence fileName,
                                String charset)
        Where possible, gets a value for a HTTP Content-Type header based on a given filename (based on known filename extension mappings), including character set information.

        Character set information can only be included for text/* or application/* MIME types.

        Parameters:
        fileName - the non-null filename.
        charset - the name of the charset to use. If null, the default of UTF-8 is applied.
        Returns:
        the best-match MIME type based on known filename extension mappings.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the content type for the file is not a specific subtype of text/* or application/*, or if the charset is unsupported.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        getFileContentType(CharSequence)

      • getLastModifiedMinValue

        long getLastModifiedMinValue()
        Gets the minimum value for the Last-Modified HTTP response header that the server will normally allow.

        This threshold value is related to the start time of this HTTP service, and is designed to avoid issues that may arise when files are copied and timestamps become misleading. Other issues this helps to avoid include timestamps for files embedded in OSGi bundles and theme packages. Such issues would generally appear as the "wrong" versions of files being accessed from client (browser) caches.

        Returns:
        the minimum normal threshold time, as milliseconds from the Unix epoch. This is rounded down to the nearest second, for easier comparison with HTTP date header conventions.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        IHttpServiceCall.setLastModified(long)

      • createAddress

        IAddress createAddress(CharSequence relativeUri)
        Creates a parsed address, using a "parent directories and file item" idiom. The parsed address excludes the base path (this makes no difference if addresses are accessed via the server's root path). The query string is considered to contain parameters only, and is not therefore considered to be part of the address.
        Parameters:
        relativeUri - a non-null URI relative to the base path. Must start with "/". Directories and files are separated by "/" characters. All other characters will be URL-encoded using UTF-8 (the calling method must not pre-encode characters in the URI).
        Returns:
        the parsed address.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified relativeUri cannot be converted to a valid address representation.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        IHttpServiceCall.createAddress(CharSequence)

      • createUri

        URI createUri(CharSequence relativeUri)
        Creates a URI, relative to the root URI of the server endpoint. The resulting URI will include the base path.
        Parameters:
        relativeUri - a non-null URI relative to the base path. Must start with "/". Directories and files are separated by "/" characters. All other characters will be URL-encoded using UTF-8 (the calling method must not pre-encode characters in the address part of URI, but is responsible for encoding any query string parameters if provided).
        Returns:
        the URI.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified relativeUri string cannot be converted to a valid URI object.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        IHttpServiceCall.createUri(CharSequence)
